{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 18:11:21.905135", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — fat‑tree EBGP lab\nPrepared: now\n\nSummary (high level)\n- Core routing (FRR/BGP across leaves, spines, super‑spine) appears healthy and converged: all required BGP peers are established and the expected /24 host networks are present in BGP and in the routers' RIBs.\n- There is an access/host‑level connectivity anomaly affecting pc_0_1. Traffic from pc_0_1 to remote hosts fails with immediate \"Destination Host Unreachable\".\n- Root cause (localized): pc_0_1 is misconfigured with the wrong IP/subnet and also duplicates the IP of pc_0_0 (both show 10.0.0.2). Because pc_0_1 is on a different subnet than its attached leaf interface (leaf_router_0_1 has 10.0.1.1 on the host link), pc_0_1 cannot reach its gateway and therefore cannot reach remote networks.\n\nKey evidence and findings\n\n1) End‑to‑end reachability test (summary)\n- Most host-to-host pings in the lab are successful (0% loss) per the reachability probe.\n- Exception observed: pc_0_1 -> pc_3_3 had no data in the global reachability summary, and an explicit ping attempt failed:\n\n  From pc_0_1 -> pc_3_3 (4 packets):\n  - Result: 4 transmitted, 0 received, +4 errors, 100% loss\n  - ICMP error text: \"From 10.0.0.2 icmp_seq=X Destination Host Unreachable\"\n\n  Interpretation: The local machine (or a device on-link with IP 10.0.0.2) is generating the ICMP unreachable.\n\n2) Host interface and routing state — pc_0_1\n- ip addr / ifconfig (pc_0_1):\n  - eth0: inet 10.0.0.2/24\n  - default route: via 10.0.0.1 dev eth0\n  - ip neigh returned empty (no resolved gateway MAC)\n  - ifconfig counters: TX packets 9, RX packets 0 (pc sent packets but received none)\n\n  Key point: pc_0_1 expects gateway 10.0.0.1 but has no ARP/neighbor resolution and no RX traffic.\n\n3) Host interface and routing state — pc_0_0\n- ip addr / ifconfig (pc_0_0):\n  - eth0: inet 10.0.0.2/24\n\n  Key point: pc_0_0 also has IP 10.0.0.2 — duplicate address with pc_0_1.\n\n4) Leaf router attached to pc_0_1 — leaf_router_0_1\n- Interface for host side (eth8) shows:\n  - eth8: inet 10.0.1.1/24\n  - eth8 RX packets: 9 (matches pc_0_1 TX), but eth8 TX packets: 0\n- Kernel route table on leaf_router_0_1 includes:\n  - 10.0.1.0/24 dev eth8 proto kernel scope link src 10.0.1.1\n  - 10.0.0.0/24 reachable via other next hops via BGP (but not directly on eth8)\n\n  Interpretation: leaf_router_0_1 expects its directly connected host subnet to be 10.0.1.0/24, but pc_0_1 is configured as 10.0.0.2. Packets from the PC are seen on the router's link (eth8 RX 9) but the router has a different local IP for that link, so no neighbor/gateway resolution for 10.0.0.1 exists on that link. That explains why the router does not reply to ARP / does not forward on behalf of the PC.\n\n5) BGP and routing fabric health\n- show ip bgp summary and routing table snapshots (sampled from leafs/spines/super‑spine):\n  - BGP sessions are UP (peers established) across leaf/spine/super-spine devices.\n  - The advertised /24 host subnets are present in each router's BGP table and in the RIB (multiple paths present).\n  - Routing entries for remote pods/prefixes exist and are being selected.\n  - No BGP peers are in Active/Idle/Down state in the samples collected.\n\n  Conclusion: core control plane (FRR/BGP) and inter-router connectivity are functioning normally.\n\nAnomalies detected (concise)\n- Duplicate host IP: both pc_0_0 and pc_0_1 configured with 10.0.0.2 (duplicate address).\n- pc_0_1 is in the wrong L2/L3 subnet relative to its attached leaf router: leaf_router_0_1 eth8 is 10.0.1.1/24 while pc_0_1 is 10.0.0.2/24.\n- pc_0_1 has no neighbor (ARP) entries for its configured gateway (10.0.0.1), and receives no packets from remote hosts — local forwarding fails.\n- Symptom: pc_0_1 cannot reach remote hosts (immediate unreachable returned).\n\nLocalization (which devices are the problem)\n- Faulty device: pc_0_1 (host configuration issue).\n- Secondary symptom: IP conflict with pc_0_0 (pc_0_0 also configured 10.0.0.2). This duplicate IP could cause ambiguous / misleading behavior on the shared L2 segments and confusion when ARP occurs.\n- Network devices (leaf_router_0_1, spines, super‑spine) appear to be operating correctly per BGP summaries and routing tables; leaf_router_0_1 sees traffic arriving on its host port but its configured host subnet does not match the PC's address.\n\nRoot cause analysis\n- Direct root cause: pc_0_1 has an incorrect IP address/configuration (10.0.0.2/24) that does not match the subnet configured on the leaf router port it is attached to (10.0.1.1/24). Because the PC's configured default gateway (10.0.0.1) is not present on the local wire (and in addition the IP value is duplicated by pc_0_0), the PC cannot resolve the gateway or place traffic onto the routed fabric. The kernel/host reports \"Destination Host Unreachable\" when attempting to ping remote hosts because local routing/ARP failure prevents forwarding.\n- The duplicate IP (pc_0_0 and pc_0_1 both using 10.0.0.2) is an important contributing issue — it may cause packet/ARP confusion and is itself indicative of misconfiguration.\n\nOther observations (non‑fault)\n- BGP tables show multiple alternate AS paths (expected in multi‑tier EBGP fat‑tree); the control plane shows full adjacency and prefix propagation; no anomalies observed at spine/super‑spine level.\n- No systemic packet loss or high RTTs were observed across the rest of the fabric in the reachability tests.\n\nEvidence snippets (representative)\n- pc_0_1 ifconfig/ip:\n  - eth0: inet 10.0.0.2/24, default via 10.0.0.1\n  - TX packets 9, RX packets 0\n- leaf_router_0_1 host port:\n  - eth8: inet 10.0.1.1/24, RX packets 9, TX packets 0\n- duplicate on pc_0_0:\n  - eth0: inet 10.0.0.2/24\n- ping from pc_0_1 to 10.3.3.2:\n  - \"From 10.0.0.2 ... Destination Host Unreachable\"\n\nRecommended next steps for validation (not remediation)\n- Confirm physical attachment mapping: verify which leaf interface is connected to pc_0_1 and ensure addressing plan matches (collecting ARP tables would help).\n- Confirm whether pc_0_1 should be in 10.0.1.0/24 (as leaf_router_0_1 eth8 indicates) or whether leaf_router_0_1 should be 10.0.0.1 — this will identify whether host or leaf config is intended.\n- Resolve duplicate IP: determine which host legitimately owns 10.0.0.2 and identify any unintended duplicate assignments.\n\nEnd of report\n\nIf you want, I can run additional on‑device checks (ARP tables, ip neigh on routers, or examine the exact topology mapping) to further confirm which side is misconfigured. I did not apply any mitigations per instructions.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 33995, "output_tokens": 3340, "total_tokens": 37335, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 33280}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1472}}}
